%Paper:   cotton\r%NL%','','0599f.jpg','0599b.jpg','E','On the front of both series of euro banknotes, windows and doorways are shown. They symbolise the European spirit of openness and cooperation. The bridges on the back symbolise communication between the people of Europe and between Europe and the rest of the world.%NL%%NL%\n\nThe windows, doorways and bridges shown on the banknotes are stylised illustrations, not images of, or from, actual constructions.%NL%%NL%\n\nOther design elements are:%NL%\n\nthe name of the currency - euro - in both the Latin (EURO) and the Greek (EYP?) alphabets for the first series; the Europa series has the name also in the Cyrillic alphabet (EBPO);%NL%\nInitials of the European Central Bank in five linguistic variants - BCE, ECB, EZB, EKT and EKP for the first series andin nine linguistic variants for the second series:%NL%\nBCE: French, Italian, Portuguese, Romanian, Spanish%NL%\nECB: Czech, Danish, Dutch, English, Latvian, Lithuanian, Slovak, Slovene, Swedish%NL%\nЕЦБ: Bulgarian%NL%\nEZB: German%NL%\nEKP: Estonian, Finnish%NL%\nEKT: Greek%NL%\nEKB: Hungarian%NL%\nB?E: Maltese%NL%\nEBC: Polish%NL%\nthe symbol © indicating copyright protection; and%NL%\nthe EU flag.%NL%%NL%\n\n<b>Signatures</b>%NL%\n\nEach banknote bears the signature of either Willem F. Duisenberg, Jean-Claude Trichet or Mario Draghi – the first, second and third Presidents of the European Central Bank respectively. These banknotes are all equally valid.%NL%%NL% \n\nSource: http://www.ecb.europa.eu\n\n','','<b>Under UV light</b>%NL%%NL%\n- the paper itself does not glow.%NL%\n- fibres embedded in the paper appear, coloured red, blue and green.%NL%\n- the flag of the European Union looks green and has orange stars.%NL%\n- the signature of the ECB President turns green.%NL%\n- the large stars and small circles on the front glow. The map, bridge and value numeral on the back appear in yellow.%NL%',124),('EUR',5,2013,'',NULL,'Dimensions: 120 x 62 mm','','0513f.jpg','0513b.jpg','',' A new series, called \"the Europa series\", is being released from 2013; the first €5 notes entered circulation on 2 May 2013.%NL%The new series include slight changes, notably the inclusion of the face of the mythological princess Europa in the watermark and in the hologram stripe%NL%%NL%\n\nThe design of the Europa series is based on the “ages and styles” theme of the first series. However, the new banknotes have been visually modified in order to give them a fresh look and to accommodate a range of new and enhanced security features, which will also make it easy to differentiate between the two series.%NL%%NL%\n\nThe old series will gradually be withdrawn. The ECB will announce in due course when the old notes will lose their legal tender status. However, they will not lose their value and it will be possible to exchange them for new notes at Eurosystem central banks indefinitely','','<b>Under standard ultraviolet light</b>:%NL%\n - The paper itself does not glow, i.e. it does not emit light and is dark.%NL%\n - Small fibres embedded in the paper appear. Each fibre shows three different colours.%NL%\n - On the front, the stars in the EU flag, the small circles as well as the large stars glow yellow. Several other areas also glow yellow.%NL%\n - On the back, a quarter of a circle in the centre of the banknote as well as several other areas glow green. The horizontal serial number and a stripe appear in red.%NL%%NL%%NL%\n\n<b>Under special ultraviolet light (UV-C)</b>:%NL%\nOn the front, the small circles in the centre glow yellow, the large stars and several other areas glow orange. The € symbol also becomes visible.',1659),('EUR',10,2002,'',NULL,'Dimensions:   127 х 67 mm\r%NL%Main Colour:    red\r%NL%Paper:   cotton','','1099f.jpg','1099b.jpg','E','On the front of both series of euro banknotes, windows and doorways are shown. They symbolise the European spirit of openness and cooperation. The bridges on the back symbolise communication between the p