nt image - denomination is printed in a shimmeringq transparent colour. It is especially easy to see when the light falls on the feature at a particular angle;\r%NL%%NL%B - Watermark only visible against the light;\r%NL%%NL%C - Intaglio Digits - the denomination of the note is produced by an intaglio process;\r%NL%%NL%D - The Perforated Number (microperf) - the contours of the denomination are \"embroidered\" by micro laser perforation (for 10, 20 and 50 francs - perforated are only the contours of the figures, for larger denominations figures are \"tightly perforated\") and are seen when held up to the light;\r%NL%****************************\r%NL%Initially, the perforated number was used on the large banknotes only. Since 2000, this feature has also been incorporated into the 10, 20 and 50 franc notes. Until all the banknotes have been replaced, small denominations with and without the perforated number will be in circulation. Both versions will, however, remain legal tender.%NL%****************************\r%NL%%NL%E -Optically Variable Ink (OVI) - the denomination of the banknote is printed with special ink. The color of the symbol changes whenever the light falls on it from a different angle;\r%NL%%NL%F - Ultraviolet Digits - the denomination on the left edge of the note appears dark under UV light and brightly fluorescent on the right side; \r%NL%%NL%G - Metallic Digits - the banknote denomination is reproduced in metal-coated form. When the note is tilted, the number has a silvery glitter;\r%NL%%NL%H - Tilt Effect - the banknote\'s denomination is printed in such a way that it can only be seen from un unusual angle.\r%NL%%NL%Note: (see the  50 francs banknote for  images of each individual security feature).'),(62,9,'Anti-copier device',88,32,NULL,NULL,'chf10977.jpg','Anti-copy element: Part of the special protections with letters.%NL% G - the number of the face value printed with \"metallic\" ink .%NL% The contour of the denomination is formed by micro text.