beth II was born on April 26, 1926 in London, ascended to the throne on 6 February 1952 after the death of her father King George VI.\n%NL% for the Queen of Canada, it was proclaimed in separate coronation performed at Westminster Abbey on June 2, 1953\n%NL% the background depicts a scene from the building of the Canadian Parliament - the tower alone.\n%NL% signatures printed on the obverse under greater number of par 20 in the bottom right are WPJenkins and DADodge.'),(860,2,'Back',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'202k42.jpg','Reverse side presents the art of extraordinary artist Bill Reid (William Ronald Reid) (1920-1998) - sculptor, carver, jeweler, engraver, painter, book illustrator, poet and storyteller, author of works of art made from forged metal master even canoes. All of his work, from miniscule engraved gold jewelry to monumental bronze sculptures in the spirit of culture \"Haida\". \"Haida\" are North American Indians living in British Columbia and Alaska. Bill Reid himself has Indian origins (his mother was Haida Indian tribe) and it became the most important figure in the revival of the artistic traditions of the Haida, and the whole art of the Indians of the north-western part of the American continent.\n%NL%%NL% Bank has chosen to note that four of the artistic works of the hill:\n%NL%%NL% In the foreground is considered the peak of the work of Bill Reid \"Spirit of Haida Gwaii\" - a canoe floating in eternity, complete with a strange crowd of mythical creatures. Haida Gwaii is the land of the Haida tribe - beautiful islands in British Columbia (the islands \'Queen Charlotte\'). For this work Reed was inspired by Haida-clay sculpture from the 19th century depicting a sailing canoe in humans and animals. Sculpture Reed has two options - Bronze, also known as \"Black Canoe\" is located in the embassy of Canada in the U.S. and emerald made of jade - at Vancouver International Airport. Plaster model of the sculpture is set out in the Canadian Museum of Civilization in Quebec.\n%NL%%NL% in the lower left corner of the banknote depicts the work \"The Raven and the First Man\" - a wooden sculpture made of yellow cedar, exhibited in the Museum of Anthropology at the University of British Columbia.\n%NL% dedicated to the legend of the appearance of man. It tells how one day the raven - the most powerful of mythical creatures in Haida culture saw a lonely beach in Haida Gwaii unusual shell, inside which there were several small human beings. He persuaded them to leave the shell and join his wonderful world. They hesitated, but curiosity compelled them to submit a partially open a giant clam and so came the first Haida-man.\n%NL% There is a miniature version of this sculpture made of gold and another option - onyx.\n%NL%%NL% right behind the dugout to see another work of Bill Reid - bronze frieze \"Mythic Messengers\" - mythical creatures in a strange communication with each other.\n%NL% This frieze is owned Fonadatsiyata Bill Reid (exposed in Vancouver International Airport), and another version is presented in the Canadian Museum of Civilization in Quebec.\n%NL%%NL% fourth piece of the hill shown in the bill is \"Xhuwaji\" - \"Naida Grizzly Bear\" - the painting was established as a model of a ceremonial drum Haida Indian tribe and has multiple versions. The version used for banknote exhibit from the permanent collection of the \"Artists - children\" in North Vancouver.\n%NL%%NL% Short text is printed underneath the large number of nominal \"20\" to highlight the importance of art in the life of mankind - this is a quote from the work \"Hidden Mountain\" Gabrielle Roy (1909-1983) - a of the most important figures in the French-Canadian literature.\n%NL%%NL%\n\"Could we ever know each other\n%NL% in the slightest without the arts? \"'),(860,3,'Watermark',265,110,160,130,'202k43.jpg','Watermark:\r%NL%Located in the middle side of a banknote. \r%NL%Represent three-dimensional halftone image of the portrait of a baknote - of Queen Eli