\n%NL%%NL% - four images that illustrate the historical path of the nation toward democracy and equality in Canada - a statue of a group of 5 women known as the \"Famous Five\" fragment of the front page of the newspaper, which appeared on October 18, 1929 , with the words \"Women are Persons, Les femmes sont des personnes.\" (\"Women are persons\") Pendant - prize in the name of Teresa Kazgreyn at the top of the bill - the scales of justice.\n%NL%%NL% Who are the \"Famous Five\": in the early 20th century, they ensure the rights of Canadian women, then changing their status. The case of \"personality\" is famous in the annals of political science. In 1927, Emily Murphy and four other prominent women want the Supreme Court of Canada to answer the question whether the word \"person\" used in a legal document, the British North America Act includes women. After 5 weekly debates the answer is \"no.\" Then the famous Five turns to the Privy Council in England, who was then the highest judicial authority in Canada on Oct 18, Lords of the council decided that women are also included in the term \"persons.\" So famous quintet won the right for women to serve in the Senate. Bronze monument to the five women enjoying victory was made by Barbara Peterson was placed on the Olympic Plaza in Calgary in 1999 to commemorate the 70th anniversary of the judgment in the case \"personality\", and in 2000 this statue was and placed before Parliament.\n%NL%%NL% Kazgreyn Who is Teresa (1896-1981): Canadian political leader (Quebec), a fighter for human rights and freedoms not only for Canada but for the world. In 1970 he became a member of the Senate. Chosen to illustrate the theme of the note \"deepen my profile of the nation\" because its efforts are helping to create and promote the principles of equality and justice in Canadian society. The award in her name is awarded annually by the government of one man and one woman in his life shown remarkable achievements in volunteering.'),(867,3,'Watermark',255,116,170,130,'502k43.jpg','Watermark:\r%NL%A thumbnail halftone image of the portrait, depicted on the obverse is viewed against light in the lower middle area on the both sides of the banknote.\r%NL%Aside from him has a secont, contrasting watermark representing the number of nominal 50.'),(867,4,'Security thread',380,50,53,125,'502k44.jpg','Security thread:\n%NL% Vertical ribbon woven into the paper over its entire width. From the back of the note she leaves part of the surface in the form of a series of metal rectangles, like the dotted line that changes color from gold to green when changing the viewing angle.\n%NL% Seen against the light strand is continuous. Is imprinted repeated microprinted CAN50.'),(867,5,'Intaglio printing',45,172,NULL,NULL,'502k45.jpg','Embossing:\n%NL% Only the obverse - embossed printed larger number of par 50, the image of the coat of arms in the lower left area and the text BANK OF CANADA • BANQUE DU CANADA.'),(867,6,'Holographic stripe',42,94,NULL,NULL,'502k46.jpg','Hologram: \r%NL%A vertical line at the left end of the front side. \r%NL%When changing the viewing angle, the brightly colored numbers \"50\" and the maple leaves \'move\' in silver metallized band. Colors vary between all the nuances of the rainbow at changing the angle at which the light falls. \r%NL%The maple leaves are divided into color in the middle. Upon closer examination you can see small numbers \"50\" in the background of the three-dimensional strip. \r%NL%The ribbon has rounded ends.'),(867,7,'See-through register',305,130,125,135,'502k47.jpg','See through register:\n%NL% segments of the numbers 5 and 0 of the nominal number 50 printed on the front of overlap with the segments printed on the reverse side and against the light when considering observed complete picture of the number \"50\" no differences of various parts.'),(867,8,'Visually impaired aid',352,15,NULL,NULL,'502k48.jpg','Visually impaired aid: Embossed points in upper end of the