light.'),(885,6,'Security thread 2',183,96,273,97,'1t2k46.jpg','Security Thread 2:\n%NL% Vertical strip embedded in the paper, partially visible on the obverse.\n%NL% in normal light and direct gaze observed red shiny metallic sections that change to green by tilting the banknote. In the light, the thread appears as a continuous band printed on it in negative numbers on par \"1000KR\".'),(885,7,'Intaglio printing',175,34,43,131,'1t2k47.jpg','Embossing:\n%NL% rosettes and the number of par on the obverse are printed in relief, with a thick layer of ink that feels during caress the surface.'),(928,1,'Front',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'10_051.jpg','The obverse:\r%NL%%NL%Portrait of Sir John A.Makdonald, the first Prime Minister of Canada, one of the \"fathers\" of the confederation.\n%NL% Born in Glasgow - Scotland in 1815, emigrated to Canada in 1820, died on June 6, 1891\n%NL% He headed the government from 1867 to 1873 and from 1878 to 1891\n%NL% In Canada honors and remembers Makdonad role in the creation of the state and the implementation of the major project for the passage of the transcontinental railroad. As an expert in constitutional law MacDonald participated in the drafting of the legislation of British North America, through which established the federal system combining the first four provinces of the country - Ontario, Quebec, Nova Scotia and New Bransuik (now the provinces of Canada 10) July 1, 1867\n%NL% During the time when he was the prime minister of the country, Canada achieved rapid progress and prosperity - Manitoba, British Columbia and Prince Edward Island joined the Confederation, completed the last section of the Canadian Pacific transcontinental railroad line, etc.\n%NL%%NL% on the background in the middle area of ??the face is visible image of the Library of Parliament in Ottawa, Ontario - the only surviving part of the original Parliament building.\n%NL% signatures of note are: left - P. Jenkins, authorized senior manager of the Bank and to the right - DA Dodge - Governor of the Bank of Canada.'),(928,2,'Back',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'10_052.jpg','Reverse:%NL% Design is devoted to the following topics.\n%NL%%NL% 1. * Remembrance * - commemorative scene - in the right area of the note is visible illustration in which representatives of different generations pay tribute to those who died in the struggle for peace in the official celebration in Canada on November 11 (the day on which in 1918 completed first World war)\n%NL%%NL% Pigeons - international symbol of peace and earth globe surrounded by the words \"Au service de la paix - In the service of peace\" (ie, \"In the Service of Peace\") is seen in the background .\n%NL%%NL% 2. * Keeping the peace * - shown are representatives of national land and sea military and peacekeeping forces.\n%NL%%NL% 3. Poem: on the left side of the banknote are printed verses from a poem by Colonel John McCray \"In Flanders Fields\" and its French adaptation of \"Au champ d\'honneur\" with a garland of red poppies symbolizing peace and honor those who died for peace.'),(928,3,'Watermark',265,115,165,115,'10_053.jpg','Watermark:\r%NL%Halftone image of the portrait of the banknote and in lower are - contrasting image of the number of a nominal 10.\r%NL%Visible against the light. They are invisible if its not against a penetrating light.'),(928,4,'Security thread',378,50,45,100,'10_054.jpg','Security thread:\n%NL% vertical stripes implanted in the paper that comes in part from the reverse side. Visible rectangles with metallic color that changes from gold to green when changing the viewing angle. Small text \"CAN10\" is printed on the strip. Against the light seen as a continuous dark line.'),(928,5,'See-through register',300,140,125,138,'10_055.jpg','See through register:\n%NL% Details of the digits 1 and 0 of the number of the face value printed on the face is superimposed with the details printed on the reverse side and against the light when considering observed complete image of the numeral \"10\" without differences of various parts.'),(928,6,'Intaglio printing',380,140,NULL,NULL,'10_056.jpg','Embossing:\n%NL% intaglio printing method is applied to the front side.\n%NL% in sliding a finger across the surface of the bill feel the raised print larger number of par 10, the national emblem of Canada on the lower left and vertical text BANK OF CANADA • BANQUE DU CANADA.'),(928,7,'Holographic stripe',45,101,NULL,NULL,'10_057.jpg','Hologram: \r%NL%A vertical line at the left end of the front side. When changing the viewing angle, the brightly colored numbers \"10\" and the maple leaves \'move\' in the brilliant metallized band. The colors change between all the nuances of the rainbow in case of change the angle at which the light falls (iridescence). \r%NL%The maple leaves are divided into color in the middle. At closer examination you can see small numbers \"10\" in the background of the strip. \r%NL%The strip has rounded edges.'),(928,8,'Hidden image',97,121,NULL,NULL,'10_0511.jpg','Hidden image:\r%NL%\r%NL%By special ink on the portrait printed text \"BANQUE DU CANADA 10 BANK OF CANADA\", which is invisible under normal light, but when illuminated by ultraviolet light appears fluoresce yellow and red.\r%NL%'),(928,9,'Microprint',412,135,NULL,NULL,'10_059.jpg','Micro text:\n%NL%\n%NL% Small, distinct characters, very well readable through a magnifying glass: in diagonal lines in the fields around the portrait right of the image of the parliamentary building in the large number of nominal \"10\".\n%NL%'),(928,10,'Microprint',NULL,NULL,2,151,'10_0510.jpg','micro text\n%NL%\n%NL% text of the poem on the left side of the reverse side is printed with micro characters.\n%NL% Intertwined figures of nominal \"10\" in the vertical bars in the margin of the note.'),(928,11,'New Signature',350,170,NULL,NULL,'10_0511.jpg','The emission, dated 2006 (face) in 2008 printed banknote series with a new combination of signatures: on WP Jenkins (as the previous emission) and MJ Carney (new signature - right).'),(928,12,'Printed 2009',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'10_0512.jpg','Printout 2009:\r%NL%\r%NL%The design is the same, but in the lower central portion of the reverse side after the date \"PRINTED IN\" is \"2009\". Signatures of the authorized persons on the face are the W.P. Jenkins and M.J. Carney.'),(1103,1,'Design',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'102k51.jpg','The obverse features red background images of the Statue of Liberty\'s torch, the phrase we the people from the United States Constitution, a smaller metallic representation of the Statue of Liberty\'s torch, orange and yellow background color, a borderless portrait of Hamilton, and to the left of Hamilton small yellow 10s whose zeros form the EURion constellation. %NL%%NL%The reverse features small yellow EURion 10s and have the fine lines removed from around the vignette of the United States Treasury building.\n%NL%%NL%\nThe redesigned currency remains the same size and uses the same, but enhanced portraits and historical images as the older-design bills, and importantly, continues to be recognized around the world as quintessentially American.'),(1103,2,'Portrait',170,128,NULL,NULL,'102k52.jpg','The first U.S. Secretary of the Treasury (1789–95), Alexander Hamilton, is currently featured on the obverse of the bill, while the U.S. Treasury Building is featured on the reverse. %NL%%NL%Hamilton is one of two non-presidents featured on currently issued U.S. bills, the other being Benjamin Franklin on the $100 bill. %NL%%NL%Hamilton is one of only four people featured on U.S. paper currency (1861 to the present) who was not born in the continental United States, as he was from the West Indies. \n%NL%%NL%The Redesigned $10 Note%NL%\nThe oval borders and fine lines surrounding the portrait of Secretary Hamilton on the front, and the United States Treasury Building vignette on the back, have been removed. The portrait has been moved up and shoulders have been extended into the border. Additional engraving details have been added to the vignette background.'),(1103,3,'Symbols of Freedom',243,116,NULL,NULL,'102k53.jpg','A symbol of freedom representing an icon of Americana has been added to the redesigned $10 bill. Two images of the torch carried by the Statue of Liberty are printed in red on the front of the redesigned bill. A large image of the torch is printed in the background to the left of the portrait of Secretary Hamilton, while a second, smaller metallic red image of the torch can be found on the lower right side of the portrait. The symbols of freedom differ for each denomination.'),(1103,4,'Federal Reserve Indicators',20,52,NULL,NULL,'102k54.jpg','A universal seal to the left of the portrait represents the entire Federal Reserve System. A letter and number beneath the left serial number identifies the issuing Federal Reserve Bank. There are 12 regional Federal Reserve Banks and 24 branches located in major cities throughout the United States.'),(1103,5,'Serial Numbers',66,28,NULL,NULL,'102k55.jpg','The recently redesigned Federal Reserve Notes, beginning with Series 1996, have two letters rather than one at the beginning of the serial number. %NL%On these notes, the first letter corresponds to the series of the note: The notes of Series 2004, beginning the next redesign, have serial numbers beginning with E; Series 2004A, with G; Series 2006, with I; Series 2009, with J; Series 2009A, with L; and Series 2013, with M. (Note that the 2006 series designation has been used for notes of two different design generations, and that it is paired with a different serial prefix letter in each case.)%NL% The second letter of each serial number now represents the issuing FRB and ranges from A through L. The last letter still can be anything but O or Z, and is still occasionally replaced by a star, with the same meaning as before.'),(1103,6,'Watermark',375,72,53,70,'102k56.jpg','Watermark:\r%NL%\r%NL%Hold the bill to light to see a faint image of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton to the right of his large portrait. It can be seen from both sides of the bill. On the redesigned $10 bill, a blank oval has been incorporated into the design to highlight the watermark\'s location.'),(1103,7,'Security thread',265,55,150,55,'102k57.jpg','Security thread:%NL%\nHold the bill to light to make sure there\'s a small thread embedded in the paper. The words USA TEN and a small flag are visible in tiny print. It runs vertically to the right of the portrait and can be seen from both sides of the bill. This thread glows orange when illuminated by ultraviolet light.'),(1103,8,'Color-Shifting Ink',385,127,NULL,NULL,'102k58.jpg','Color-changing ink:\n%NL%\nTilt the bill to check that the numeral 10 in the lower right-hand corner on the front of the bill changes color from copper to green. The color shift is more dramatic on the redesigned currency, making it even easier for people to check their money.'),(1103,9,'Microprint',170,155,NULL,NULL,'102k59.jpg','Microtext:\n%NL%\n%NL%The words THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA and TEN DOLLARS can be found below the portrait\n'),(1103,10,'Microprint',2,85,NULL,NULL,'102k510.jpg','Microtext:\n%NL% The words THE UNITED STATES OF AMERICA and TEN DOLLARS can be found vertically inside the left and right borders of the bill.'),(1103,11,'Microprint',110,106,NULL,NULL,'102k511.jpg','Microtext:\n%NL%\nThe word USA and the numeral 10 can be found repeated beneath the large printed torch.'),(1103,12,'Digital protection',110,50,370,40,'102k512.jpg','Digital protection: %NL%%NL%\n\nSmall yellow \"10\" are printed left of the portrait on the face side and around of the US Treasury on the reverse side. They are arranged under a specific scheme, called \"Yurion\" (EURion constellation). The word \"Yurion\" is a combination of the Orion constellation with similar disposition of some of its stars and EURo (euro). %NL%\nThe scheme, by which are positioned symbols, supports software recognition of digital image of bill that contains EURion constellation. Then this special software can block the user trail to make a reproduction and process the banknote using digital color scanning and photocopying equipment for eventual production of fakes. The idea and the name of the technology belong to Markus Kuhn (2002). %NL%\nIn the scheme zeros are important - they are circles with a diameter of 1 mm (Also called \"circles of Omron\") in a specific geometric arrangement - five circles arranged as part of the stars of the constellation Orion. %NL%\nPrograms such as Adobe Photoshop or Paint Shop Pro, finding this circuit, refuse to open scanned images of banknotes and modern color photocopiers with appropriate software refuse to copy them.'),(1103,13,'Intaglio printing',197,37,225,119,'102k513.jpg','Intaglio printing:\n%NL%\n%NL% The portrait on the obverse and the image of the building of the Treasury on the reverse.'),(1103,14,'Series 2006',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'102k514.jpg','Signatures on banknotes series 2006'),(1103,15,'Series 2009',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'102009.jpg','Signatures on banknotes series 2009'),(1134,1,'Differences from 1999 emission',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'02051.jpg','Differences from 1999emission:\r%NL%\r%NL%The differences in the change of the year of issue written on it - in 2005 and the signatures of the Governor of the BNB and the Chief Cashier of the National Bank in the lower right corner of the front of \r%NL%the banknote.\r%NL% \r%NL%The new banknote is printed on a paper with a much better quality than the previous and it is expected the depreciation time to be extended for about 30%.\r%NL%'),(1134,2,'Watermark',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'02052.jpg','Watermark:\r%NL%\r%NL%Three-dimensional halftone image of upright lion.\r%NL%'),(1134,3,'Security thread',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'02053.jpg','Security thread:\n%NL%\n%NL% Built-in paper tape with negative microprinted \"БНБ\".'),(1134,4,'Intaglio printing',128,129,NULL,NULL,'02054.jpg','Embossing:\n%NL%\n%NL% on the front s