NL%\n%NL% chess fields printed at specific positions on the front and back are covered completely when the banknote against the penetrating light in a rectangle monitor the number of nominal \"50\" - light on a dark background.'),(1213,7,'Latent image',78,169,NULL,NULL,'502k67.jpg','Hidden image:\n%NL%\n%NL% in the lower left part of the obverse on the jacket of John Doe, when the banknote at an acute angle (15-20 degrees), there is a picture of the number \"50.\"\n%NL%'),(1213,8,'Raised Printing for the Visually Impaired',385,210,NULL,NULL,'502k68.jpg','Character recognition banknote citizens with impaired vision:\r%NL%\r%NL%Embossed image of two identical triangles with their apexes pointed at each other in the lower right corner of the obverse.\r%NL%\r%NL%  '),(1213,9,'Microprint',358,159,NULL,NULL,'502k69.jpg','Microtext:\r%NL%\r%NL%The big picture of the nominal number 50 at bottom right angle of the front side is filled with repeating microsymbols \"50 ЛЕВА\".'),(1213,10,'Microprint',204,41,NULL,NULL,'502k610.jpg','Microtext:\r%NL%\r%NL%Horizontal lines with text \"ПЕНЧО СЛАВЕЙКОВ\" in the background left of the portrait on front side; \r%NL%- repeating mini-text \"ПЕНЧО СЛАВЕЙКОВ\" in two vertical, underlining big script ПЕНЧО СЛАВЕЙКОВ  lines right of the portrait; \r%NL%- in the background right of the portrait - slanting lines with pale yellow minitext \"ПЕТДЕСЕТ ЛЕВА\".'),(1213,11,'Microprint',NULL,NULL,122,30,'502k611.jpg','Microtext:\r%NL%\r%NL%Tawny coloured minitext \"ПЕНЧО СЛАВЕЙКОВ\" on the top left part of coloured field on the back side.'),(1213,12,'Special fluorescence',NULL,NULL,164,168,'502k612.jpg','Special fluorescence - a bi-fluorescence:\r%NL%\r%NL%On the reverse side of the banknote appears bas relief Pencho Slavejkov, illuminated in blue when illuminated by ultraviolet light with a wavelength of 365 nm and red - at 254 nm.'),(1264,1,'Differences from 2001 emission',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'blank.jpg','Differences from 2001 emission:\r%NL%\r%NL%-difference in the signature of the Governor of the Bank at the bottom of the obverse (Rimsevich).\r%NL%\r%NL%- the year printed on the lower right corner of the reverse of the \"2006\" \r%NL%\r%NL%-new to this nominal security feature - color shifting ink (OVI). The number of nominal \"5\" in the left margin on the front side is printed with this ink.\r%NL%\r%NL%- two relief images of the number of nominal \"5\" stamped over the item \"see-through register\" (stylized oak leaves) of obverse of the banknote.\r%NL%\r%NL%- rhomb-shaped micro-text “LATVIJAS BANKA” below the nominal number of \"5\" (OVI) in the left margin of the front side.'),(1264,2,'Watermark',74,73,NULL,NULL,'5062.jpg','Watermark:\r%NL%\r%NL%Halftone image of a profile of traditional young latvian woman, visible against penetrating light.'),(1264,3,'Security thread',317,114,134,92,'5063.jpg','Security thread:\n%NL%\n%NL% Metallised strip printed with its repeated \'Ls 5\'. Out partially on the reverse side and is visible as a continuous dark band is seen when the banknote against the penetrating light.\n%NL% sections that go on the reverse side of the banknote with a holographic effect.'),(1264,4,'See-through register',159,155,290,151,'5064.jpg','See through register:\n%NL%\n%NL% A stylized image of a leaf of oak. In monitoring the banknote against the light elements distributed on the face and reverse side overlap perfectly to form a complete image.'),(1264,5,'Color-Shifting Ink',79,139,NULL,NULL,'5065.jpg','Changing ink:\n%NL%\n%NL% A new security feature in the modified bill. The number of par 5 in the left pane of the front is covered with ink that has OVI - effect, ie changes color when changing the viewing angle.'),(1264,6,'Microprint',97,177,35,67,'5066.jpg','Microtext:\r%NL%\r%NL%Front side - Rhomboid formed with microtext “LATVIJAS BANKA” in the rectangle at the left field, under the nominal number \"5\".\r%NL%\r%NL%Back side - series of oblique lines with repeating nominal number \"5\" with changing size.\r%NL%'),(1264,7,'Latent image',402,160,NULL,NULL,'5067.jpg','Latent image:\r%NL%\r%NL%A hidden image of the nominal digit \"5\" and the letters \"Ls\" is printed in a frieze on the right side of the obverse of the banknote. The image becomes visible when the banknote is observed under a certain angle \"catching\" the light.'),(1264,8,'Anti-copier device',29,157,NULL,NULL,'5068.jpg','Prevention stripe:%NL%%NL% on the left side of the rectangle in the left side of the face - a vertical embossed tape repeated 4 times the nominal figure \"5\" visible when tilting the banknote.'),(1264,9,'Anti-copier device',154,98,NULL,NULL,'5069.jpg','Anti-copy feature:%NL%%NL% A new security feature in this issue relief number of nominal \"5\" printed twice over oak leave (the element \"through register\") on the left side of the face.'),(1264,10,'Intaglio printing',152,205,NULL,NULL,'50610.jpg','Embossing:\n%NL%\n%NL% basic graphical elements on the obverse are printed by the method \"intaglio\".\n%NL%\n%NL% point in the upper left area of ??the face is a sign of relief help in recognizing the face value of the blind.'),(1264,11,'Emission 2009',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'50611.jpg','Issue 2009:\n%NL%\n%NL% design is saved, the signature too - this Governor of the Bank of Latvia Ilmars Rimsevics.\n%NL%-to-date is the date on the reverse side - 2009.'),(1265,1,'Design of the banknote',295,67,87,130,'202k71.jpg','Year printed on the front is 2006, although the bill was released in 2007\n%NL% front side continues to present a portrait of HM Elizabeth II, Queen of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland.\n%NL% The main image on the reverse side of the banknote profile of Adam Smith (1723-1790), Scottish philosopher and political economist, known for his work \"Wealth of Nations\", which laid the foundations of the modern economy. The full title of the book is \"Study of the nature and causes of the wealth of nations\" and was published in 1776 in Edinburgh. The work is one of the first attempts to trace the historical development of industry and commerce in Europe. Smith is a supporter of liberal economics and capitalism, supply and demand determine the market, rejecting strong state intervention in the economy.\n%NL% right of the portrait of Adam Smith is printed fragment of the original engraving \"The division of labor in the production of heat\" and below - quote from \"The Wealth of Nations.\" (A.Smit brings example of the impact of the division of labor even in a minor manufactory as heat).\n%NL% Another famous work of Adam Smith\'s \"Theory of Moral feelings\", published in 1759 In it he promoted his idea that people are born with an innate sense of morality, that morality is a product of nature, not of reason and rejects the prevailing until thesis that morality is defined by the laws, rules and regulations.\n%NL%%NL% Adam Smith was the first Scot to appear on the bill of the Bank of England.\n%NL% His portrait can be seen on the Scottish banknotes of 50 pounds of Clydesdale Bank.'),(1265,2,'Watermark',47,124,364,111,'20072.jpg','Watermark - hold the 20 GBP note up to the light and you will see an image of the Queen\'s portrait together with a bright 20 GBP.'),(1265,3,'Security thread',NULL,NULL,163,118,'20073.jpg','Metallic thread - there is a metallic thread embedded in every banknote. This appears as silver dashes on the back of the 20 GBP note. If you hold the note up to the light the metallic thread appears as a continuous dark line.'),(1265,4,'Raised print ',371,169,NULL,NULL,'20074.jpg','Raised print - by running your fingers across the front of the 20 GBP note you can feel raised print in areas such as the words \'Bank of England\' and in the bottom right corner, around the number 20.'),(1265,5,'Holographic strip',139,153,NULL,NULL,'20075.jpg','Holographic strip - the strip on the 20 GBP note has a number of foil patches along its length which contain alternating holographic images. The positioning of the patches varies along the strip. When the note is tilted, one hologram shows a multi-coloured image of Adam Smith, the other changes between a multi-coloured symbol of GBP and the number 20. The number 20 is also embossed on the strip and is positioned in the same place on every note - just to the right of the signature of the Chief Cashier.'),(1265,6,'See-through register',105,105,310,96,'20076.jpg','See-through register - hold the 20 GBP note up to the light and you will see coloured irregular shapes printed on the front and back that combine to form the Ј symbol.'),(1265,7,'Microprint',284,200,NULL,NULL,'20077.jpg','Microlettering - Using a magnifying glass, look closely at the lettering beneath the Queen\'s portrait on the 20 GBP note - you will see the value of the note written in small letters and numbers.'),(1265,8,'Microprint',201,188,238,195,'200711.jpg','Microlettering :\r%NL%\r%NL%Repeating microtext \"20 Pounds\" is printed as a background of the value of the note \"20\" in a form of diagonal paralel lines.\r%NL%\r%NL%Repeating  microtext \"TWENTY POUNDS\"is printed in horizontal line above the text \"Pounds\" in the middle bottom area of the front side.\r%NL%\r%NL%Microtext of repeating \"BOE\" (Bank of England) is readable with a magnifier in the background of the bottom back side.'),(1265,9,'Paper and print quality',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'20078.jpg','Paper and print quality:\r%NL%\r%NL% Banknotes are printed on special paper that gives them their unique feel. \r%NL%\r%NL%Print Quality - the printed lines and colours on the 20 GBP note are sharp, clear and free from smudges or blurred edges.'),(1265,10,'UV feature',203,44,NULL,NULL,'20079.jpg','Ultra-violet feature - if you look at the front of the 20 GBP note under a good quality ultra-violet light the number 20 appears in bright red and green. Randomly spread bright red and green flecks are also visible on both the front and back of the note. The remainder of the note appears dull in contrast.'),(1265,11,'Unique numbering',NULL,NULL,353,200,'200710.jpg','Unique numbering - a unique number is printed horizontally and vertically on the back of the 20 GBP note. The horizontal number is in the bottom right corner and consists of multi-coloured letters and numbers, increasing in height from left to right. The vertical number runs down the left side and has letters and numbers that are the same height and colour.'),(1265,12,'New Signature 2011',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'2012.jpg','New signature of new Chief Cashier - Chris Salmon.'),(1304,1,'Description',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'m2991.jpg','The euro coins have a common side and a national side. The national side indicates the issuing country.%NL%%NL%\nThe common side of the €2 coins depict the denomination on the left, the currency, map of Europe and twelve stars on the right. Coins minted from 1999 to 2006 depicted the EU15, rather than the whole European continent, which is on coins minted from 2007.%NL%%NL%\nOn 7 June 2005, the European Council decided that the common side of the €0.10 to €2 coins should be brought up to date to reflect the enlargement of the EU in 2004. The design still retains all elements of the original designs, including the twelve stars, but the map of the fifteen states is replaced by one showing the whole of Europe as a continent, without borders, to stress unity. These coins were not mandatory for existing eurozone members when introduced in 2007, but became so for every member in 2008.%NL%%NL%\nCyprus is shown several hundred kilometres north west of its real position in order to include it on the map. On the €1 and €2 coins, the island is shown to be directly east of mainland Greece.%NL%\nCoins from Italy (including San Marino and the Vatican City), Austria and Portugal show the more recent design only if they are dated “2008” or later.%NL%%NL%\n<b>Diameter (mm):</b> 25.75%NL%\n<b>Thickness (mm): </b>2.20%NL%\n<b>Weight (g): </b>8.50%NL%\n<b>Shape: </b>Round%NL%\n<b>Colour: </b>Outer part: silver; inner part: gold%NL%\n<b>Composition: </b>Outer part: copper-nickel; inner part: three layers: nickel brass, nickel, nickel brass%NL%\n<b>Edge: </b>Edge lettering, fine milled%NL%%NL%\nThe common sides of the coins were designed by Mr Luc Luycx of the Royal Belgian Mint. On the 2-euro coin his signature is visible under the O of the word EURO on the common side.\n%NL%%NL%\nThe €2 coin is the most counterfeited.\n'),(1304,2,'Attention!',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'m2.jpg','<b>Attention!</b>%NL%%NL% The coin of 1  new Turkish lira is very similar to the 2 euro coin (and there are also similarities between 50 Kurush (half Turkish Lira) and the 1 Euro coins).%NL% This could create confusion for the vending machines (located in the airports) in the Eurozone. It is common a vending machine to accept coins of 1 Turkish Lira instead of 2 euro coin.'),(1305,1,'Description',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'m22k71.jpg','The euro coins have a common side and a national side. The national side indicates the issuing country.%NL%%NL%\nThe common side of the €2 coins depict the denomination on the left, the currency, map of Europe and twelve stars on the right. Coins minted from 1999 to 2006 depicted the EU15, rather than the whole European continent, which is on coins minted from 2007.%NL%%NL%\nOn 7 June 2005, the European Council decided that the common side of the €0.10 to €2 coins should be brought up to date to reflect the enlargement of the EU in 2004. The design still retains all elements of the original designs, including the twelve stars, but the map of the fifteen states is replaced by one showing the whole of Europe as a continent, without borders, to stress unity. These coins were not mandatory for existing eurozone members when introduced in 2007, but became so for every member in 2008.%NL%%NL%\nCyprus is shown several hundred kilometres north west of its real position in order to include it on the map. On the €1 and €2 coins, the island is shown to be directly east of mainland Greece.%NL%\nCoins from Italy (including San Marino and the Vatican City), Austria and Portugal show the more recent design only if they are dated “2008” or later.%NL%%NL%\n<b>Diameter (mm):</b> 25.75%NL%\n<b>Thickness (mm): </b>2.20%NL%\n<b>Weight (g): </b>8.50%NL%\n<b>Shape: </b>Round%NL%\n<b>Colour: </b>Outer part: silver; inner part: gold%NL%\n<b>Composition: </b>Outer part: copper-nickel; inner part: three layers: nickel brass, nickel, nickel brass%NL%\n<b>Edge: </b>Edge lettering, fine milled%NL%%NL%\nThe common sides of the coins were designed by Mr Luc Luycx of the Royal Belgian Mint. On the 2-euro coin his signature is visible under the O of the word EURO on the common side.\n%NL%%NL%\nThe €2 coin is the most counterfeited.\n'),(1306,1,'Description',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'m1_1.jpg','The euro coins have a common side and a national side. The national side indicates the issuing country.%NL%%NL%\nThe common side of the €1 coins depict the denomination on the left, the currency, map of Europe and twelve stars on the right. Coins minted from 1999 to 2006 depicted the EU15, rather than the whole European continent, which is on coins minted from 2007.%NL%%NL%\nOn 7 June 2005, the European Council decided that the common side of the €0.10 to €2 coins should be brought up to date to reflect the enlargement of the EU in 2004. The design still retains all elements of the original designs, including the twelve stars, but the map of the fifteen states is replaced by one showing the whole of Europe as a continent, without borders, to stress unity. These coins were not mandatory for existing eurozone members when introduced in 2007, but became so for every member in 2008.%NL%%NL%\nCyprus is shown several hundred kilometres north west of its real position in order to include it on the map. On the €1 and €2 coins, the island is shown to be directly east of mainland Greece.%NL%%NL%\nCoins from Italy (including San Marino and the Vatican City), Austria and Portugal show the more recent design only if they are dated “2008” or later.%NL%%NL%%NL%\n<b>Diameter (mm):</b> 23.25%NL%\n<b>Thickness (mm):</b> 2.33%NL%\n<b>Weight (g):</b> 7.50%NL%\n<b>Shape:</b> Round%NL%\n<b>Colour:</b> Outer part: gold; inner part: silver%NL%\n<b>Composition: </b>Outer part: nickel brass; inner part: three layers: copper-nickel, nickel, copper-nickel%NL%\n<b>Edge:</b> Interrupted milled %NL%%NL%\nThe common sides of the coins were designed by Mr Luc Luycx of the Royal Belgian Mint. His signature on all euro coins is visible as two L letters connected together (LL). On the 2-euro coin, this is visible under the O of the word EURO on the common side.\n'),(1307,1,'Description',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'m12k71.jpg','The euro coins have a common side and a national side. The national side indicates the issuing country.%NL%%NL%\nThe common side of the €1 coins depict the denomination on the left, the currency, map of Europe and twelve stars on the right. Coins minted from 1999 to 2006 depicted the EU15, rather than the whole European continent, which is on coins minted from 2007.%NL%%NL%\nOn 7 June 2005, the European Council decided that the common side of the €0.10 to €2 coins should be brought up to date to reflect the enlargement of the EU in 2004. The design still retains all elements of the original designs, including the twelve stars, but the map of the fifteen states is replaced by one showing the whole of Europe as a continent, without borders, to stress unity. These coins were not mandatory for existing eurozone members when introduced in 2007, but became so for every member in 2008.%NL%%NL%\nCyprus is shown several hundred kilometres north west of its real position in order to include it on the map. On the €1 and €2 coins, the island is shown to be directly east of mainland Greece.%NL%%NL%\nCoins from Italy (including San Marino and the Vatican City), Austria and Portugal show the more recent design only if they are dated “2008” or later.%NL%%NL%%NL%\n<b>Diameter (mm):</b> 23.25%NL%\n<b>Thickness (mm):</b> 2.33%NL%\n<b>Weight (g):</b> 7.50%NL%\n<b>Shape:</b> Round%NL%\n<b>Colour:</b> Outer part: gold; inner part: silver%NL%\n<b>Composition: </b>Outer part: nickel brass; inner part: three layers: copper-nickel, nickel, copper-nickel%NL%\n<b>Edge:</b> Interrupted milled %NL%%NL%\nThe common sides of the coins were designed by Mr Luc Luycx of the Royal Belgian Mint. His signature on all euro coins is visible as two L letters connected together (LL). On the 2-euro coin, this is visible under the O of the word EURO on the common side.\n'),(1308,1,'Description',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'m22k71.jpg','On March 25, 2007 is the 50th anniversary of the foundation to the European Union. In this case, all euro area countries that are members of the EU (ie without Vatican, San Marino and Monaco) issued new commemorative 2-euro coins that are legal tender throughout the euro area.\n%NL% Austrian coin dedicated to the so-called. Rome Treaty was put into circulation on 26 March 2007 One side is a design common to the Eurozone. The other is a memorial design - the folder with the Treaty of Rome, open the page with the signatures of the six countries (France, Germany, Italy, Belgium, Netherlands and Luxembourg), which in 1957 established the European Economic Community, which became later European Union.\n%NL% In the background is depicted jack Campidoglio square in Rome, designed by Michelangelo.\n%NL% inscriptions carved on coin:\n%NL% - VERTRAG VON ROM, 50 JAHRE (Treaty of Rome, 50 years);\n%NL% - EUROPA (Europe)\n%NL% - REPUBLIK OSTERREICH (Austria)\n%NL% in different national editions of this coin three texts appear in the language or in Latin. Image remains the same for all countries.'),(1394,1,'Front',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'202k71.jpg','The obverse shows a portrait of Stefan Stambolov (1854-1895).\n%NL%%NL% Born in the town of Turnovo. He studied in his native city (1866-1869), and then won a scholarship to the seminary in Odessa (1870-1872). Expelled from the seminary because of connections with the Russian revolutionaries. In 1873, a teacher in Turnovo, then transferred to Romania, where falls among Bulgarian revolutionary emigration. As a member of BRCC plays an important role in the preparation of Stara Zagora (1875) and the April Uprising (1876). Participated in the Russo-Turkish War (1877-1878) as Secretary of the military envoy Slavic Committee and take care of Bulgarian volunteers. After the liberation in 1878, he settled in Turnovo as a lawyer. Actively participated in the movement against the Treaty of Berlin. Active member of the Liberal Party. MP in II-VIII (1880-1895) Ordinary National Assembly Deputy Speaker of II (1880) and IV (1884) and president of the IV (1884-1886) OHC.\n%NL% participated in the Serbo-Bulgarian War (1885) as a volunteer. After the dethronement of Battenberg (9 August 1886) led a counter-coup, and after the abdication of the prince enters the Regency Council. In 1887 convened the Third Grand National Assembly election of Bulgarian Prince Ferdinand. At that time secede from the Liberal Party and laid the foundations of the Popular Party (1887-1895). As chairman of the Council of Ministers and Minister of the Interior (1887-1894) introduced dictatorial management methods (ie. Stambolovist mode).\n%NL% a policy of separation from Russia and seeks to move towards Austria-Hungary, Germany and the UK. Conflict with Ferdinand, which compels him to resign (19 May 1894). Attacked on July 3, 1895 in Sofia by his political opponents and on July 6, died of wounds inflicted.\n%NL% call it \"the Bulgarian Bismarck\".'),(1394,2,'Back',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'202k72.jpg','On the reverse side depicts the facade of the National Assembly, fragments of Eagle Bridge and Lion Bridge - architectural monuments related to the activity of Stefan Stambolov as a statesman, a fore seen a facsimile of his manuscript.\n%NL%%NL% building, which meets the National Assembly was built in three stages. Its design wa