ed by a special process of printing and would be difficult to replicate by counterfeiters.%NL%%NL% against visible light continuous band of light and dark areas.'),(1627,4,'See-through register',50,47,342,47,'50124.jpg','See through register\n%NL%\n%NL% against the penetrating light is visible exact matches and combining the images of the cross printed on one spot on the obverse and reverse of the banknote.'),(1627,5,'Iridescent stripe',NULL,NULL,346,180,'50f125.jpg','Iridescent tape:\r%NL%\r%NL%On the right side of the reverse of the banknote - wide vertical bar with iridescent coating - pearls gloss, which \"catches\" the light by tilting the banknote - to create the difficulty for counterfeiters.'),(1627,6,'Intaglio printing',268,59,NULL,NULL,'50f126.jpg','Embossing:\n%NL%\n%NL% intaglio - printing is applied to the graphic elements of the obverse.'),(1627,7,'Microprint',152,62,NULL,NULL,'50f127.jpg','Microtexts:\r%NL%\r%NL%At various places on the obverse of the banknote - readable with a magnifier.'),(1649,1,'Watermark',53,114,402,135,'1hf121.jpg','Watermark:\r%NL%%NL%Halftone image of a ram`s head and a cross.\r%NL%'),(1649,2,'Security thread',300,85,NULL,NULL,'1hf122.jpg','Security Thread 1:\n%NL%%NL% A narrow vertical thread woven into the paper fully visible when viewed against the penetrating light. There magnnitni properties (recognition of banknote).'),(1649,3,'3D Security thread',369,130,58,113,'1hf123.jpg','3 D Security Thread%NL%%NL% Vertical Bar implanted in the paper coming out partially on the obverse as a dotted line. On the visible areas are \"moving\" left-right and up-down pattern - cross in a circle. Illusion of motion (3D) was established by special technology and can hardly be reproduced by counterfeiters.\n%NL%%NL% Against visible light continuous band of lighter and darker areas.'),(1649,4,'Iridescent stripe',NULL,NULL,376,104,'1hf124.jpg','Iridescent tape:\r%NL%\r%NL%On the right side of the reverse of the banknote - wide vertical bar with iridescent coating - pearls gloss, which \"catches\" the light by tilting the banknote - to create the difficulty for counterfeiters.'),(1649,5,'See-through register',48,45,377,38,'1hf125.jpg','See through register\n%NL%%NL% against the penetrating light is visible exact matches and combining images of ornament printed in a specified location on the obverse and reverse of the banknote.'),(1649,6,'Intaglio printing',171,54,NULL,NULL,'1hf126.jpg','Embossing:\n%NL%%NL% intaglio - printing is applied to the graphic elements of the obverse.'),(1649,7,'Microprint',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'1hf127.jpg','Microtexts:\r%NL%%NL%At various places on the obverse and reverse of the banknote - integrated into the design, visible under a magnifying glass.'),(1659,1,'General Information',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'05131.jpg',' A new series, called \"the Europa series\", is being released from 2013; the first €5 notes entered circulation on 2 May 2013.%NL%The new series include slight changes, notably the inclusion of the face of the mythological princess Europa in the watermark and in the hologram stripe%NL%%NL%\n\nThe design of the Europa series is based on the “ages and styles” theme of the first series. However, the new banknotes have been visually modified in order to give them a fresh look and to accommodate a range of new and enhanced security features, which will also make it easy to differentiate between the two series.%NL%%NL%\n\nThe old series will gradually be withdrawn. The ECB will announce in due course when the old notes will lose their legal tender status. However, they will not lose their value and it will be possible to exchange them for new notes at Eurosystem central banks indefinitely'),(1659,2,'Watermark',71,100,371,112,'05132.jpg','A portrait watermark:\r%NL%%NL%Halftone image - the portrait of the mythological figure Europa. This is why the feature is also called the “portrait watermark”, to distinguish it from the watermark of the first series. %NL%%NL%Alongside Europa, the watermark also depicts the value and the main design feature of the banknote. \r%NL%\n\n'),(1659,3,'Security thread',171,125,245,132,'05133.jpg','Security Thread\n%NL%%NL% Look at the banknote against the light. The security thread appears as a dark stripe. The € symbol and the value of the banknote can be seen in tiny white lettering in that stripe.'),(1659,4,'Hologram',392,149,NULL,NULL,'05134.jpg','The hologram:\r%NL%%NL%A vertical, 7 mm wide silvery stripe on the front of the banknote, shows a portrait of the mythological figure Europa, a gateway, the € symbol and the value numeral of the banknote.'),(1659,5,'SPARK security feature',50,185,NULL,NULL,'05135.jpg','Security Feature SPARK ®\n%NL%%NL% \nThe emerald number is a shiny number displayed on the front of the banknote. When the note is tilted, a band of light moves up and down. The number also changes colour from emerald green to deep blue depending on the angle at which the banknote is tilted.\n%NL%%NL%%NL%\n\n\nThe SPARK® technology is one of the latest developments of the Swiss company SICPA, specializing in security inks and solutions for banknotes, identification documents and other products. %NL%\nSPARK® is a dynamic, bright, easily identifiable security element. It is created during the printing process , making it difficult to reproduce and therefore very safe security element.%NL%\nThe new element combines a bright deep color and a strong dynamic aspect expressed in the movement of the brighter color along the printed element or in the change of the brighter color into the darker one.%NL%\nIt is an optical security instrument based on the magnetic pigments location control with the help of magnetic fields within the ink layer. The OVMI® ink (optically variable magnetic ink) contains optically variable pigments produced with the help of vacuum technology. \n'),(1659,6,'Glossy stripe',NULL,NULL,150,158,'05136.jpg','Glossy stripe:\r%NL%Tilt the banknote – a gold-coloured stripe will appear on the back. It shows the value and the € symbol.'),(1659,7,'Raised print',187,44,NULL,NULL,'05137.jpg','Raised print:\n%NL%%NL% Special printing makes the ink feel raised or thicker in the main image, the lettering and the value numerals on the front of the banknotes. To feel the raised print, run your finger over it or scratch it gently with your fingernail.'),(1659,8,'Raised print',5,68,NULL,NULL,'05138.jpg','Raised print:\n%NL%%NL% On the front, there is a series of short raised lines on the left and right edges. They make it easy to identify the banknote, especially for visually impaired people. '),(1659,9,'Raised print',333,94,NULL,NULL,'05139.jpg','Raised print:\n%NL%%NL% Special printing makes the ink feel raised or thicker in the main image, the lettering and the value numerals on the front of the banknotes. To feel the raised print, run your finger over it or scratch it gently with your fingernail.'),(1659,10,'Microprint',235,25,NULL,NULL,'051310.jpg','Microtext:\r%NL%%NL%The two stars above the arch (recto) are filled tightly with repeated text \"5\" and \"EURO\" in Latin, Greek and Cyrillic. In the top star the text is negative and in the bottom star - in a positive.'),(1659,11,'Microprint',392,27,NULL,NULL,'051311.jpg','Microtext:\r%NL%%NL%In the hologram stripe - wavy lines with text \"5\" and \"EURO\".'),(1659,12,'Microprint',NULL,NULL,29,64,'051312.jpg','Microtexts:\r%NL%%NL%Integrated into the design on the back side - easily legible under a magnifying glass.'),(1659,13,'Fibres',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'051313.jpg','Fluorescent fibres:\r%NL%%NL%Under UV light small fibres embedded in the paper appear. Each fibre shows three different colours - blue, green  and red.'),(1659,14,'Under special ultraviolet light (UV-C)',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'051314.jpg','<b>Under special ultraviolet light (UV-C) -  UV rays with a short wavelength (UVC - 253.7 nm)</b>:%NL%\nOn the front, the small circles in the centre glow yellow, the large stars and several other areas glow orange. The € symbol also becomes visible.'),(1659,15,'Infrared',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'051315.jpg','Infrared:\r%NL%%NL%Under infrared light, on the front of the banknote, only the emerald number, the right side of the main image and the silvery stripe are visible. On the back, only the value numeral and the horizontal serial number are visible.'),(1659,16,'Serial Numbers',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'051316.jpg','Serial Numbers:\n%NL%%NL%The serial numbers on this series are the two numbers printed on the back of the banknote: a horizontal number printed in black and a vertical number printed in a different colour.%NL%\n\nThe horizontal number comprises two letters and ten digits. The first letter identifies the printing works – see the list below. The second letter has no particular meaning; it simply makes more serial numbers possible.%NL%%NL%\n\nPrinting works and letters%NL%\n\nBanque Nationale de Belgique – Z%NL%\nBank of Greece – Y%NL%\nGiesecke & Devrient GmbH (Munich) – X%NL%\nGiesecke & Devrient GmbH (Leipzig) – W%NL%\nF?brica Nacional de Moneda y Timbre – V%NL%\nBanque de France – U%NL%\nCentral Bank of Ireland – T%NL%\nBanca d\'Italia – S%NL%\nBundesdruckerei GmbH – R%NL%\nJoh. Enschede Security Printing BV – P%NL%\nOesterreichische Banknoten und Sicherheitsdruck GmbH – N%NL%\nValora – M%NL%\nNot assigned - L%NL%\nNot assigned – K%NL%\nDe La Rue Currency (Gateshead) – J%NL%\nDe La Rue Currency (Loughton) – H%NL%\nNot assigned – G%NL%\nNot assigned – F%NL%\nOberthur Fiduciaire – E%NL%\nPolska Wytw?rnia Papier?w Warto?ciowych – D%NL%\nNot assigned - C%NL%\nNot assigned - B%NL%\nNot assigned - A%NL%\n\n'),(1659,17,'Banknote print code',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'051317.jpg','Banknote Print Code:\r%NL%%NL%Each of the seven Euro banknote denominations carry a small six-character printing code. This printing code is organised in the form of letter-digit-digit-digit-letter-digit, which is then broken into four groups, uniquely identifying each banknote and revealing printing location and production information. Some users often refer to this code as the \'short code\'..\r%NL% V003F1.'),(1659,18,'Signature',75,50,NULL,NULL,'051318.jpg','Signature:\n%NL%%NL% The 5 EURO banknote bears the signature of the current Presidents of the European Central Bank - Mario Draghi.\n'),(1659,19,'EURion constellation',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'051319.jpg','EURion constellation:\ra pattern of five small yellow circles which is repeated across white areas of the banknote on the front and back. %NL%%NL%\n\nThe name \"EURion constellation\" was coined by Markus Kuhn, who uncovered the pattern in early 2002 while experimenting with a Xerox colour photocopier that refused to reproduce banknotes. The word is a portmanteau of EUR, the euro\'s ISO 4217 designation, and Orion, a constellation of similar shape.%NL%%NL%\n\nThe EURion constellation first described by Kuhn consists of a pattern of five small yellow, green or orange circles, which is repeated across areas of the banknote at different orientations. The mere presence of five of these circles on a page is sufficient for some colour photocopiers to refuse processing. \nTechnical details regarding the EURion constellation are kept secret by its inventors and users. A patent applicationsuggests that the pattern and detection algorithm were designed at Omron Corporation, a Japanese electronics company. It is also not clear whether the feature has any official name. The term \"Omron anti-photocopying feature\" appeared in an August 2005 press release by the Reserve Bank of India. In 2007 it was picked up in an award announcement by a banknote collectors society.\n'),(1659,20,'See-through register',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'051320.jpg','See through register\n'),(1660,1,'Description',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'02121.jpg','Euro coins 2 Euro issued by the Principality of Monaco in 2012\n%NL% Circulation: 100,000\n%NL% Issue Date: July 1, 2012\n%NL% circulation coins are legal tender throughout the euro area.\n%NL% Theme Design: 500 